My exams are over so I will be actively present for the communication hereafter.
Things that I looked as discussed on the first meeting:

1) Looked into the way how `solve` solves exponential and logarithmic equations.
2) Filtered out tests from solve module and looked at them.
3) Trying to figure out how the API of `transolve` would look like. 

As of now I think the transolve() should contain `f,  symbols, domain, **flags` as its params (Don't know to what extent `flags`can be used here, but included here for taking care of recursive calls).

I am still looking as to how the flow of the API would go.  One thing that I thought was to have independent helpers as per the type of equations. Like if we need to solve `log` equations identify it and call its helpers, if it is lambert type, again identify it and call its helper.
For exponential eqs majority of the equations can be handled by `invert` (need to add a case for such eqs), other equations can be factored to P.O.S form and can be handled by _solveset().

Need suggestion on this:

I am actually thinking to make a generalised function to get logarithmic singularities (maybe add in `calculus.singularities`??).
For this we need to divide into two, if the function is solved in real domain and if it is in complex-domain. In case for complex we can simply iterate over the log terms, extract the argument of the log and solve it (the result will be the branch point). But this will not be true for real-valued functions as therefore we could something similar but rather returning a single branch point, we can return a set from `-oo` to the point.
